Pay to Play: College Athletics Spending and Success Before NIL

STOR 320.02 Group 15

April 28, 2025

INTRODUCTION

College football is a multi-billion-dollar industry where schools invest heavily in hopes of winning games, building national prestige, attracting students, and strengthening alumni ties. Yet despite the widespread belief in the “spend to win” model, it remains unclear whether simply spending more actually guarantees greater success — especially when considering the wide differences in academic reputation, enrollment size, and conference affiliation among universities.

While powerhouse programs like those in the “Power Five” conferences tend to dominate both financially and competitively, many questions remain. Which types of investments — such as coaching salaries, recruiting budgets, or football operations — actually matter most? Does money have the same impact at highly ranked academic schools compared to others? And how do different revenue streams like ticket sales or athletic aid shape a team’s investment strategy and, ultimately, its success?

This project explores two main questions:

  • First, to what extent do financial investments predict college football success across different conferences, and how does this relationship vary by a university’s academic level and size?

  • Second, how do differences in football success and athletic revenue affect the composition of athletic investment strategy by universities that differ by competitive level?

Answering these questions matters now more than ever. As the college sports world rapidly shifts in the wake of NIL policies, understanding how money shaped success in the pre-NIL era provides an important baseline. This research also offers insights for smaller programs trying to do more with less — and for bigger programs questioning whether their massive spending truly pays off. Moving beyond the simple “more money equals more wins” narrative, this study aims to uncover a more complete picture of what drives success in college football and financially for the overall athletic department.

DATA

The information utilized for this project was mostly obtained from Sports Viz Sunday, which is edited by Simon Beaumont and Spencer Baucke, and provided by Data World. This data set provided both NCAA financial information—revenue, spending, and highest-investing categories—and football performance data such as wins, losses, and win percentage for Division I institutions between 2005 and 2017. Admissions and academic data, including the number of students enrolled and institution types, were obtained separately from the U.S. Department of Education’s College Scorecard database, which pulls together extensive details on colleges nationally. We decided to look at the 2005–2017 years in order to include trends before Name, Image, and Likeness (NIL) policies were implemented, so the financial and competitive trends examined would represent the pre-NIL era of traditional collegiate athletics before direct athlete compensation became prevalent.

To examine the association between financial investment and sports success, we combined NCAA financial data and football performance statistics for the period between 2005 and 2017. The significant financial variables included Total Revenues, Total Expenses, Coaches Compensation, Facilities and Equipment spending, Athletic Student Aid, Game Expenses and Travel, Donor Contributions, Recruiting, and more. These investment sources were chosen because they both represent internal program decision-making on expenditures and external sources of funding significant to a program’s growth. On the performance side, football-specific metrics such as Wins, Losses, and Winning Percentage were used, since football disproportionately contributes to overall athletic revenue at most universities. To more fully control for structural variation across programs, schools were grouped into High-Major, Mid-Major, and Low-Major categories based on football conference affiliation, using only conferences that remained intact over the study period (with independent schools and discontinued conferences like the Big East and WAC excluded). Academic controls, such as undergraduate enrollment and football spending normalized per student, were further added to consider investment trends by institutional academic type. Together, the variables selected provided an overall profile of how competitive greatness, financial efforts, scholarly emphasis, and top-line revenue generation relate to the collegiate athletic scene.

The clear conclusion is that High-Major programs spent the most in each category, experienced the highest rate of growth, and generated considerably more revenue than Mid-Major and Low-Major programs. This speaks to the colossal conference level budget differences and suggests that variation in financial resources is a fundamental driver of long-run competitive and financial outcomes across college athletics.

To provide an overview of the dataset, we created a barbell plot displaying each school’s average football investment percentile and winning percentile over the years 2005–2017. For each program, total football investments and winning percentages were averaged across the 12 years and converted into percentiles. Each school is represented by a line connecting the football investment percentile to the winning percentile, visualizing the correlation between the two variables. Overperforming schools, highlighted in blue, are the schools whose winning percentile exceeds their investment percentile, whereas for vice versa, they are classified as underperforming and are highlighted in green. The barbell plot indicates that there is a positive correlation between the financial investment and the winning rate in college football, but a notable number of schools either outperform or underperform relative to their financial resources. This figure serves as a descriptive foundation for the further analysis of how financial variables relate to athletic success.

RESULTS

We built a ridgeline density plot to explore variance in football expenditure across institutions of varying academic quality, normalizing by undergraduate enrollment to create a “Football Spending Per Student” variable. To better visualize differences across schools with highly skewed budgets, we applied a log transformation. Institutions were classified into four academic levels based on median ACT scores: “Low” (approximately the 30th percentile), “Medium” (50th to 65th percentile), “High” (70th to 85th percentile), and “Very High” (90th percentile and above). To provide emphasis points, median expenditure lines were overlaid. The plot reveals a clear positive correlation between academic selectivity and football investment, with “Very High” academic institutions spending significantly more per student. Although the distributions generally shift to the right with higher academic levels, noticeable overlap remains, particularly among “Medium” and “High” categories. This indicates that while stronger academic reputation tends to correspond with greater football investment, other factors such as conference affiliation, donor contributions, and ticket sales also play substantial roles in shaping football expenditures.

We selected three primary revenue sources: Ticket Sales, Institutional and Government Support, and NCAA/Conference Distributions (including media rights and postseason football revenues), and calculated each as a percentage of total athletic revenue for each university. Universities were grouped into Major Levels (High-Major, Mid-Major, and Low-Major), and average percentages were computed within each group. The results were visualized using a grouped bar chart in ggplot2. The chart shows that High-Major programs rely heavily on NCAA/Conference Distributions and Ticket Sales, with minimal dependence on Government Support. Mid-Major programs exhibit a more balanced distribution across the three sources, while Low-Major programs are predominantly reliant on Institutional and Government Support, with relatively little contribution from Ticket Sales and Distributions.

This research examines the correlation of athletic investment trends to football performance and how personal investment drives total athletic revenue. Programs were split by football winning percentage, as a measure of performance quartile, and average spending in major categories was compared. Football was used in classification since it disproportionately contributes to revenue generation, though the spending figures account for investment in all athletics, and only those institutions with football programs were examined. More successful programs (69.2% to 100% winning percentage) consistently spent more on facilities, coaches’ salaries, and had more funding from donors, while categories like athletic student aid and game expenses saw less increases at varying levels of wins, which shows they are not as significant to athletic achievement. To support this, a linear regression model that predicted total athletic revenues was established using subset selection to find the most influential financial variables. The most recent model used game expenses and travel, equipment and facilities, coaches’ salaries, student aid athletics, and donor contributions. Estimated revenues had a high correspondence with realized revenues (Adjusted R-squared = 0.9728), and no critical multicollinearity was encountered. Coaches’ salaries had the highest impact on revenue, followed by operating expenses, and these findings would imply the budgetary importance of spending on these components in order to maximize competitive as well as financial outcomes.

To further investigate how financial investments impact football team success, a multi-step modeling approach was applied to NCAA data from 2005 to 2017. After cleaning and standardizing financial fields, such as donor contributions, facilities spending, and coaches’ compensation, extreme outliers were clipped to improve the models readability. Scatter Plots with linear regression lines were used to visualize the relationships between total wins and six major investment categories: Athletic Student Aid, Coaches’ Compensation, Donor Contributions, Facilities and Equipment, Recruiting, and Total Revenues, on total wins. The financial values are scaled in millions of dollars. Additionally, a multiple linear regression model was constructed to predict Total Revenues based on Football Wins and investment categories, enabling us to quantify how both performance and spending drive a program’s financial success. Both these techniques offer us wonderful views, where the regression plots explore individual relationships. The results reveal several clear patterns. Donor Contributions and Total Revenues have the strongest positive relationships with Football Wins, suggesting that external funding and diversified revenue streams heavily influence team success. Facilities and Equipment investments also correlate well with wins, while Recruiting and Athletic Student Aid show more moderate effects. Interestingly, Coaches Compensation shows a flatter relationship, implying that simply paying coaches more does not guarantee a proportionate rise in victories without broader program support. The multiple regression model confirms that both wins and specific types of spending significantly predict a school’s revenue, although Donor Contributions appear to carry disproportionate weight compared to internal investments like Student Aid. Four figures, including faceted scatterplots, a coefficient bar plot, and a predicted versus actual revenue plot, were used to visualize the findings and support the conclusions based on data above.

CONCLUSION

Our project aimed to answer two general questions: first, how financial investments predict college football success across different conferences, and second, how different types of financial support, such as ticket sales and athletic aid, influence athletic spending strategies and football performance at universities with varying academic and competitive profiles. Results indicate a high positive correlation between spending and win rates: programs that spent more on broad categories like facilities, donor relations, and recruiting tended to win more. But not all investments were created equal—donor giving and facilities expenditures were far superior predictors of success than categories like student aid or coaching stipends in isolation.

These results are highly relevant to everyday life, especially with college sports economics still up in the air following NIL. They confirm that while money matters, where money is being spent is still more critical. Sports programs aiming to maximize competitive success should spend money on durable goods like facilities and creating donor bases at the expense of merely raising pay. This has significant implications for programs with limited resources: rather than simply trying to outspend rivals in every category, schools can concentrate on certain fiscal approaches to enhance competitiveness. Similarly, university administrators, policymakers, and donors should be interested in these results because they show that smarter, more strategic investment—not just bigger budgets—is the key to long-term athletic and fiscal success.

Subsequent research could expand on this paper by employing more current NIL-related financial data and experimenting with other variables like individual player performance, transfer portal matrices, or academic support investments. Access to richer data sets involving more granular fundraising by sport, alumni involvement scores, or the age and quality of athletic facilities would allow even more accurate modeling. More advanced machine learning techniques like gradient boosting or random forests might also be able to better identify non-linear correlations between expenditure and success that might elude more basic linear models.

Overall, the results largely upheld what was anticipated—money matters, but wiser spending matters even more. However, the strength of the results, particularly how well donor giving predicted success compared to other forms of investment, was quite unexpected. With college athletics entering an era of increased professionalization, these results will remain vital to programs at all levels seeking to balance fiscal adversity with competitiveness on the playing field.
